    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:270dd4b0-2b99-42c0-a48a-10b48b56d756",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-description</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-description"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} is a 51-year-old man who appears tired but not acutely ill, with a guarded posture and slow, careful movements when rising from a chair. He describes diffuse aching in his shoulders, neck, lower back, and thighs that has been gradually worsening over several weeks. On examination he looks mildly deconditioned, rubbing his upper arms and thighs intermittently, and reports morning stiffness and increased soreness after long workdays. He is overweight, with a stocky build, and often notes that poor sleep makes his pain feel worse the next day.\n\nHe works full-time as a warehouse shift supervisor, a role that keeps him on his feet for long hours but also involves periods of repetitive lifting and awkward body positioning. Outside work, he used to enjoy recreational fishing and weekend home improvement projects, but lately he has cut back because muscle pain and fatigue leave him less active than before. He spends most evenings watching television and admits that his exercise routine has become inconsistent over the past few years.\n\n{patientName} lives with his spouse and has two adult children who visit regularly. He is socially connected but has become more irritable and withdrawn because persistent pain is affecting his mood and sleep. He drinks coffee heavily during work shifts, has 1-2 alcoholic drinks on some weekends, and quit smoking in his early 40s. His diet is convenience-heavy, and he has been trying unsuccessfully to lose weight. He worries that the pain may indicate “something serious,” especially because it has begun to interfere with work productivity and daily comfort."
          }
        ]
      }
    },
    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:a87c1386-bfad-4948-8696-94692f40a222",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-history</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-history"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} reports several months of intermittent diffuse muscle aches that became more noticeable after increased overtime shifts at work. He denies focal trauma, chest pain, dark urine, true joint swelling, or progressive focal weakness, but says the pain is worse after lifting, prolonged standing, and poor sleep. He has a history of essential hypertension and chronic insomnia, both reasonably controlled, and no prior diagnosis of inflammatory muscle disease. He has never been hospitalized for rhabdomyolysis or autoimmune disease.\n\nHis past medical history is also notable for obesity and occasional tension-type headaches. He denies illicit drug use and reports no recent viral syndrome, tick exposure, or new vigorous exercise program. He quit smoking about 10 years ago after an estimated 15 pack-years. He drinks alcohol socially and does not report binge use. He has been taking over-the-counter ibuprofen intermittently with partial relief.\n\nThere is no history of statin use or corticosteroid dependence, and he has not had prior major orthopedic injury. He has missed a few workdays because of fatigue and generalized soreness but remains independent in activities of daily living. He is concerned the symptoms are becoming chronic and is seeking evaluation to rule out a more serious underlying condition."
          }
        ]
      }
    }
